Subject:    adding "seismo" back to the hosts.txt table
From:       <a href="?a=95837693400010&r=1&w=2">Rick Adams &lt;rick () seismo ! CSS ! GOV&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198609">1986-09-15 0:20:47</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837759026780&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837759026780&q=raw">body</a>]</b>


I have been told that you will be adding the undomained alias "seismo"
back to the hosts tables. This is supposedly because some (unnamed to
avoid embarassment) MILNET site can't handle ANY addresses that have "."
in them.

I object to this.

The correct approach is to fix their broken mail software, not hold back
everyone else.

At the risk of repeating myself, I again call for the removal of ALL
non-domained aliases from hosts.txt. Either we are running with domains
and you can remove the undomained aliases, or the entire (painful, but
necessary) process of converting to domains is a farce and we should 
admit it.

I am not implying that we should immediately convert to domain servers,
just that we not hold back everyone for the sake of a few out of date sites.
There are some sites the would still be running NCP if they were allowed.

The site in question is running 4.1BSD and delivermail. It is a (fairly)
trivial operation to run the 4.2/4.3bsd sendmail program on 4.1 BSD. I have
done it on system 5 unix systems, so it can't be difficult to do on 4.1BSD.

The sendmail code does NOT require a 4.2 or 4.3 BSD license.

---rick

